<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06224111 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06224111 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  MOUNTAIN-VIEW; BUSINESS; NEIGHBORHOOD; PLANNING; DEVELOPMENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  What's next for Castro Street? &quot;It's very important that we not sit back andput our feet up now that the project's done,&quot; said Barney Burke, MountainView's revitalization program manager.;    Burke said the city, along with a24-resident revitalization committee, will continue looking to improve CastroStreet, addressing such issues as new housing, trash maintenance, and sidestreet and alley improvements. Some work also may be considered on storefrontfacades. In the next few months, new lighting and tree guards will beinstalled on the street.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MORE PLANS FOR CASTRO  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     In the long term, the city council has just approved plans to create a moreattractive entrance into downtown from the Central Expressway area. Plannershope to create a mini-transit hub at the Evelyn Corridor that features homesand retail businesses within walking distance of public transportation, whichwould include the new light-rail stop.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Lori Aratani  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Peninsula/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910811  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  144  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday August 11, 199100224111,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>